observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following:
The MAcco to prepare a year-end adjusting entries to revert the unreleased checks totaling ₱4,428,061.77 to the cash in bank account and recognize the corresponding liability/payable account;
The MT to cancel the unreleased checks of Barangay Acacia and Pinayag with check numbers 1199103 and 1199104 due to incomplete documentation;
The MAcco to provide written explanation on the noted significant variance in the recorded book balance of the CIB-LCCA in the 20% DF and the ending balances in the SCBAA (as well as on the 5% DRRMF), and furnish proofs of reconciliations undertaken together with the MT and MBO; and
The MT and the MAcco to reconcile cashbook records with the accounting ledgers and submit the result of reconciliation to the Audit Team. Moreover, discrepancies identified should be adjusted accordingly to arrive at an updated balance and more accurate and reliable reports.

We recommended the following:
The MSWDO to submit the SSMI and distribution lists of the relief goods for the accounts of the Senior Citizen and PWD to the Accounting Office to draw a JEV and to record the expenditures using appropriate expenditure accounts;
Management to communicate with the abovementioned supplier the unaccounted welfare goods particularly the tuna flakes, 155g and to request for a refund if reconciled to be a payment of undelivered items;
The MAcco to draw the necessary adjusting journal entries to reclassify the procured Enov Lipid supplement amounting to ₱50,400.00 to the proper inventory account, Drugs and Medicines for Distribution account;
The Inventory Committee, General Services Officer (GSO), MDRRMO and MSWDO as end-user units to submit the inventory count to be undertaken semestrally, as of June 30 and December 31, and to prepare the required format of the RPCI and submit the same to the Office of Auditor every July 31 and January 31 each year; and
The MAcco to disclose in the Notes to FS the amount of inventories recognized as expense during the audit period.

We recommended the following:
The MAcco to cause the timely preparation and submission of BRSs as required by COA Circular No. 96-011;
The concerned offices to regularly adjust reconciling items identified to accurately present the LGU’s actual cash position for each period;
The MAcco together with the MT and Municipal Budget Officer to reconcile their records and the above-noted variances in the 20% DF and 5% DRRMF appearing in the FS and SCBAA, and thereafter, undertake the same regularly; and
Cash accounts to be monitored by key heads of offices consistently and should be presented fairly in accordance with IPSAS 1 and other accounting rules and regulations.
Likewise, we recommended Management to endeavor in evaluating the cause/s of the incurrence of possible cash deficit in the TF books. Further, devise concrete plans and strategies that shall be effective in monitoring the existence and availability of cash before incurrence of expenditures.

We recommended that:
The LCE and Local Sanggunian formulate clear-cut guidelines on allocations for mobile communications and data services and consider the cheaper and prevailing rates offered by mobile networks and furnish the same guidelines to the Office of the Auditor for reference in audit;
Management grant the communication allowance to officials and employees wherein communication is of utmost importance;
The MAcco and Property Officer furnish List of Employees issued with Postpaid Plan for Mobile Phone; and
The MAcco ensure completeness of supporting documents and make certain that for prepaid card users, used cards are surrendered prior to processing and payment of communication allowance to guarantee proper use of government resources.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Mayor, through the concerned office, shall ensure submission of Memorandum of Agreement and supporting documents to the Office of the Auditor within five (5) working days from perfection thereof, in keeping with COA Circular No. 2009-001;
The MAcco, MT and implementing departments shall coordinate and confirm whether projects charged to the above-mentioned fund transfers were actually completed and determine whether there are any other outstanding obligations chargeable to the funds;
The MAcco and MT shall determine if the unutilized balances accrue to the National Government Agencies or the LGU in instances of counterpart funds;
If upon verification the projects were completed and no outstanding obligations accrue to the funds, the LGU shall take the following actions:
For funds accruing the NGAs, immediately return the unexpended balances as at year-end to these Source Agencies (SA). If the SA cannot be identified, immediately remit the remaining idle funds to the Bureau of Treasury; and
For counterpart LGU funds, the Local Finance Committee shall undertake corresponding evaluation and give recommendation on the proper disposition of funds to other priority projects.

We recommended the following:
The end-user or requesting office to obtain certified copies of the (1) page of the approved Annual Procurement Plan (APP) or Supplemental APP, whichever is applicable, and (2) submitted Contract or Purchase Order stamped “Received” by COA to be attached to the Disbursement Voucher;
The BAC Secretariat to submit to the Office of Auditor copies of perfected contracts or Purchase Order along with their required attachments which shall be the basis of issuing a certified copy of the submitted Contract or Purchase Order stamped “Received” by COA;
The BAC Secretariat to issue a stamped certified copy of the page of the approved Annual Procurement Plan (APP) or Supplemental APP to facilitate regularity of all procurements;
The MAcco to require from contractors Progress Billings for progress payments which may serve as a basis for recording transactions to the Construction in Progress account and to effectively execute her pre-audit functions;
The Municipal Mayor, as Head of Agency, to sign and issue Certificate of Acceptance to signify the acceptance and satisfaction of management as to the completed projects in behalf of the LGU Kayapa; and
Management and all concerned offices are enjoined to strictly comply to the aforesaid rules and regulations on the documentary requirements and ensure that these are complete and duly attached to the disbursement vouchers to avoid audit suspension, if warranted.

We recommended that:
All the Collectors report and turnover the collections at the close of each business day and accomplish the RCD, and if in case travel time from their places of assignment is more than one day, the turn over shall be made at least once a week or as soon as the collections reach Php5,000.00 in compliance with Section 90, LTOM, 2nd Edition;
The MT closely monitor collections from cash tickets to ensure that the same is completely turned-over to the Liquidating Officer (LO), this is also in consideration that cash tickets were not pre-numbered. Additionally, issuances of cash tickets to RCCs/RCOs and every remittance of the same to the LO be properly recorded on a separate logbook to facilitate reconciliation of records;
The Collectors and/or LO to present and/or submit the duplicate copies or original copies, in case cancelled, of the above-mentioned accountable forms, as well as AF Nos. 53 and 54, and its Report of Collections and Deposits/Remittances, for audit and verification;
Implement the no erasures and alterations in preparing the OR;
Ensure that all accountable forms are properly filled-out;
The Collectors to attach in the AF51 and RCD upon remittance to the LO the original copy of the Citation Tickets issued to Violators and surrendered by them;
The Accountable Officers charged with holding of the accountable forms to also properly account the issued Citation Tickets to the PNP while the original copy be accounted by the Collectors from which it was surrendered for additional control by accounting in the permanent logbook the issue and return date of the Citation Tickets; and
Strictly comply with all the rules and regulations prescribed under Chapter III, Book 2 of the LTOM 2nd Edition and Revised Cash Examination Manual.

1. stop the granting of cash advances to Officials and employees of the LGU with unliquidated cash advance;
2. cause the immediate settlement of long overdue cash advances;
3. be cognizant with the existing regulations on the granting of cash advances and be strict in the implementation of the same; and
4. particularly the Accountant that in the exercise of her pre – audit function must see to it that compliance to regulation is carefully observed in the granting of cash advances.

1. comply with the documentary requirement under EO No. 49 in all procurement of medicines;
2. conduct physical count of inventory of drugs and medicines and make the necessary adjustments and submit the corresponding journal entry voucher (JEV) to the Auditor; and
3. strictly adhere with the provisions of Section 114 and 124 of the Manual on New Government Accounting System for Local Government Units.

We recommended that Management:

1. stop the granting of cash advances to Officials and employees of the LGU with unliquidated cash advance;

2. cause the immediate settlement of long overdue cash advances;

3. be cognizant with the existing regulations on the granting of cash advances and be strict in the implementation of the same; and

4. particularly the Accountant that in the exercise of her pre – audit function must see to it that compliance to regulation is carefully observed in the granting of cash advances.

We recommended that management direct concerned municipal officials and employees to:

1. adhere strictly to the provisions of R.A. 9184 and its IRR;

2. stop the practice of procuring goods thru reimbursement. Any alternative mode of procurement that may be resorted to should be for any exceptional cases that the same could justifiably apply. Reimbursement should be limited to cases where such supplies/materials or services cannot be provided or rendered unless immediate payment is made.
